[1] Bhutan: oranges
Date: 10 Apr 2009
Source: British Broadcasting Corporation (BBC) News [edited]
<http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/7992108.stm>


A disease is wiping out most of the orange crop in Bhutan, causing
great concern among the Himalayan country's many orchard owners. The
deadly huanglongbing (HLB) is transmitted by a small fly called a
psyllid that thrives on the leaves of the orange trees. HLB has
already caused extensive damage to orange crops in Thailand.

Oranges are the main cash crop in all but 4 districts of Bhutan and
one of the country's most important exports. HLB has already wiped
out 70 percent of orange orchards in Punakha, while other orange
growing regions like Wangduephodrang, Mongar, Zhemgang and Sarpang
are also severely hit. In Chukha, the entire orange growing region of
Baikuenza has been wiped out.

The Bhutanese Ministry of Agriculture [BMA] said the disease could
"devastate the whole citrus industry in the country if appropriate
measures are not taken soon." Dr Sangay Duba, of the National Plant
Protection Centre [NPPC], said that orchards which used to produce
200 to 300 trucks of oranges every year have barely produced 10 to 15
this year [2009]. "The situation could get worse," he warned.

Scientists say that since most orchard owners in Bhutan are absentee
landlords, they have paid little attention to plantation management
and pest control. There are 57 000 acres of abandoned or illegal
orchards in the country, from where the deadly disease is said to
have spread across the orange growing belt of Bhutan.

Bhutan's government has issued an ordinance for an investigation
team. This team has been given the right of entry into any orange
orchard and can fine farmers if they do not implement recommendations
about pest control. The BMA has proposed that illegal orchards whose
owners are not traceable should be handed over to landless farmers to
be better managed. The NPPC has also developed an "action plan" that
involves training and capacity development, quarantine of plants,
insect proof nurseries and re-planting in HLB-hit areas.

[Byline: By Subir Bhaumik]

--
