ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>

******
[3] Americas: update
Date: 2 Apr 2009
Source: FreshPlaza [edited]
<http://www.freshplaza.com/news_detail.asp?id=37938>


Citrus greening, a disease that devastates orchards and the
citrus-growing economy, recently reached Louisiana, California and
the State of Parana in Brazil. All the research organizations working
on citrus fruits have been called up.

The list of affected countries continued to grow in 2007 and 2008.
After Brazil in 2004 and Florida in 2005, Louisiana was infected in
2008. The alarm was also raised in 2008 in California, where the
psyllid, a type of sucking insect that carries the disease, was
discovered, following a similar warning from Argentine producers in
the major export zones in the northeast of that country, where the
psyllid is now present, while the disease has also been detected
across the border, in the state of Parana, Brazil.

Mediterranean producers, who have been spared the disease until now,
need to remain vigilant. _Trioza erytreae_, a psyllid that can
transmit the African form of greening, was detected in Madeira in
1994. It has also long been found in the Horn of Africa, Yemen and
Saudi Arabia.

What is needed are disease-resistant varieties and effective curative
methods. A budget of USD 20 million was recently released by
producers and the authorities in Florida. CIRAD [French Centre for
Agricultural Research for Developing Countries] has just been granted
project funding from the Florida Citrus Production Research Advisory
Council (FCPRAC).

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>

[Huanglongbing (HLB) [also called citrus greening, yellow dragon
disease], is one of the most damaging diseases of citrus crops
affecting leaves and fruits. In Asia and the Americas, it is caused
by the fastidious phloem-inhabiting bacterium _Candidatus_
Liberibacter asiaticus. However, the species may comprise several
different variants, even within a given region. Its vector is the
Asian citrus psyllid (_Diaphorina citri_), but it is also often
spread by grafting and possibly seed transmission. The vector is
specific to _Citrus_ and close relatives, and thus the disease is
confined to these crops. The other 2 species of _Ca._ L. (africanus
and americanus) can cause HLB in different areas. For more
information on HLB, see links and previous posts listed below.

In Bhutan, HLB was reported for the 1st time in 2003 and appears to
be spreading. In the Americas, the disease is spreading rapidly and,
together with citrus canker (_Xanthomonas axonopodis_ pathovar
_citri_), is considered a major threat to citrus industries.

